===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|abaisse}}, {{m|enm|abesse}}, {{m|enm|abessen}}, {{m|enm|abaishen}}, {{m|enm|abassen}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|abaisser}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|abaissier||bring low}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|a-}} + {{m|fro|baissier||to lower}}, from {{etyl|VL.|en}} {{m|la|abbassiāre||to lower}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|bassus||short of stature, low, humble}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref><ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈbeɪs/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abase.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪs|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abas}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[lower]] physically or [[depress]]; to [[stoop]]; to throw or cast down{{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{w|Thomas Shelton}}
#*: Saying so, he '''abased''' his [[lance]]''.
#: ''to '''abase''' the eye''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To lower, as in [[rank]], office, condition in life, so as to hurt feelings or cause pain; to depress; to [[humiliate]]; to [[humble]]; to [[degrade]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* Bible, Luke 14:11
#*: Whosoever exalteth himself shall be '''abased'''.
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To lower in value, in particular as altering the content of alloys in coins.<ref name=SOED/>{{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

